32
00:00:06,040 --> 00:00:09,460
<i>No, don't do that.</i> <i>We'll use the hands.</i>

33
00:00:09,530 --> 00:00:11,670
Nothing can happen, sir. I'm faster than the hands.

34
00:00:11,740 --> 00:00:13,720
I want you out of the hot room.

35
00:00:19,320 --> 00:00:21,690
<i>B.Z. Doris to I.Z. Alice.</i>

36
00:00:21,760 --> 00:00:26,070
<i>S.D.T. energy output</i> <i>is 1.8 to 3.0 joules...</i>

37
00:00:26,140 --> 00:00:28,920
<i>with rate</i> <i>two to three milliradians.</i>

38
00:00:28,990 --> 00:00:31,190
<i>And we still need</i> <i>those blankets.</i>

39
00:00:32,280 --> 00:00:34,520
No sweat, sir. Those cages are airtight.

40
00:00:34,590 --> 00:00:36,440
I wish you would sweat a little more, Toby.

41
00:00:36,510 --> 00:00:39,770
Sweat is a safeguard against some kinds of bacteria and carelessness.

42
00:00:39,840 --> 00:00:41,980
Use the hands.

43
00:01:07,710 --> 00:01:09,600
Wow!

44
00:01:09,660 --> 00:01:12,660
Transmitted by air, as we thought.

45
00:01:12,730 --> 00:01:15,250
Now we've got to determine its size.

46
00:01:15,320 --> 00:01:17,590
Could be a gas or some kind of a virus.

47
00:01:17,660 --> 00:01:21,300
<i>We'll use a hundred</i> <i>angstrom filter to begin.</i>

48
00:01:21,370 --> 00:01:23,410
About the size of a small virus.

49
00:01:40,670 --> 00:01:42,870
All systems go, sir.

50
00:01:59,320 --> 00:02:02,390
Whatever it is, it's larger than a virus.

51
00:02:02,460 --> 00:02:04,320
We'll try a one micron filter.

52
00:02:04,380 --> 00:02:06,360
Hang in there, baby.

53
00:02:16,030 --> 00:02:18,960
He must be pretty big. I'm gonna get me a fly swatter.

54
00:02:19,040 --> 00:02:21,650
Do that. Here goes with two microns.

55
00:02:33,660 --> 00:02:35,630
<i>Uh-huh.</i>

56
00:02:35,710 --> 00:02:37,600
Nasty.

57
00:02:37,660 --> 00:02:41,080
At least we'll be able to get a good look at it. Dutton to Stone.

58
00:02:41,150 --> 00:02:44,860
We've just found out its size: about two microns in diameter.

59
00:02:44,920 --> 00:02:47,770
Big enough to be a complete cell. Interesting.

60
00:02:47,840 --> 00:02:51,320
There's a good chance it's alive. Airborne transmission?

61
00:02:51,390 --> 00:02:53,530
Yes. What have you found?

62
00:02:53,600 --> 00:02:56,150
So far nothing. Our Nobel laureate here...

63
00:02:56,220 --> 00:02:58,710
won't scan on the inside because he says... All right, Ruth.

64
00:02:58,780 --> 00:03:00,310
Thanks, Charlie. Keep at it.

65
00:03:02,560 --> 00:03:04,940
It's pointless to go on scanning outside.

66
00:03:05,020 --> 00:03:07,640
If it's two microns in diameter, it would've showed up at 440.

67
00:03:07,710 --> 00:03:10,260
True, but we didn't know that before, did we?

68
00:03:10,330 --> 00:03:12,790
We'll start with five power on the inside.

69
00:03:12,860 --> 00:03:16,850
Stick to established procedure. Establishment gonna fall down and go boom.

70
00:03:16,920 --> 00:03:19,290
Switch to manual, Ruth. The interior's too irregular...

71
00:03:19,360 --> 00:03:21,140
<i>to probe on automatic.</i>

72
00:03:46,520 --> 00:03:48,380
More light, huh?

73
00:04:29,920 --> 00:04:31,830
Here's his blood value now.

74
00:04:36,190 --> 00:04:38,460
Half normal. Severely anemic.

75
00:04:44,060 --> 00:04:45,950
Wake up, sir.

76
00:04:48,030 --> 00:04:50,070
Can you hear me?

77
00:04:51,200 --> 00:04:53,050
What's your name?

78
00:04:57,980 --> 00:05:00,220
J-Jackson. What?

79
00:05:03,130 --> 00:05:04,990
Jackson.

80
00:05:08,570 --> 00:05:10,640
Stay awake, Mr. Jackson.

81
00:05:11,610 --> 00:05:13,470
Stay awake!

82
00:05:24,160 --> 00:05:26,710
Tongue blade.

83
00:05:26,780 --> 00:05:29,880
<i>Sixty-eight degrees</i> <i>on 1-4-0-7.</i>

84
00:05:29,950 --> 00:05:32,600
<i>Sixty-one</i> <i>on 1-2-0-3.</i>

85
00:05:32,670 --> 00:05:36,460
<i>Loss rate is minus 0-0-12.</i>

86
00:05:36,540 --> 00:05:39,800
<i>Please copy and confirm</i> <i>all receiving locks.</i>

87
00:05:59,160 --> 00:06:01,270
<i>You can tell you're a bachelor.</i> What was that?

88
00:06:01,340 --> 00:06:03,930
I didn't say anything.

89
00:06:06,240 --> 00:06:08,570
We're doing an isotope scan.

90
00:06:08,640 --> 00:06:11,000
How the bugs get into the body. Thought you should watch it.

91
00:06:11,070 --> 00:06:14,930
I assume it was inhaled. Not likely it's absorbed through the skin.

92
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:18,350
That's what we'll find out now: the mechanism of death.

93
00:07:10,880 --> 00:07:14,770
<i>We'll look at a replay of that</i> <i>at speed 6.</i>

94
00:07:23,450 --> 00:07:25,590
<i>That tells us what</i> <i>we want to know, Hall.</i>

95
00:07:25,660 --> 00:07:27,600
<i>The organism is inhaled.</i>

96
00:07:27,680 --> 00:07:29,880
<i>The clotting begins in the lungs</i> <i>and spreads outward.</i>

97
00:07:29,950 --> 00:07:31,990
I didn't think it possible.

98
00:07:32,060 --> 00:07:35,160
I didn't think the total volume of blood could solidify that fast.

99
00:07:35,230 --> 00:07:38,940
I hoped maybe one crucial clot might form in the brain, which was what made them go insane,

100
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:41,110
and then the rest of the blood clot more slowly.

101
00:07:41,180 --> 00:07:43,030
We'd have a chance to cure that.

102
00:07:43,100 --> 00:07:45,400
Cure what? We don't know what it is.

103
00:07:45,470 --> 00:07:49,330
Stone and Leavitt haven't been able to isolate the hellish thing.

104
00:07:49,400 --> 00:07:51,790
Of course they will in time.

105
00:07:54,520 --> 00:07:56,410
<i>Of course.</i>

106
00:08:27,230 --> 00:08:29,170
<i>Hold it.</i>

107
00:08:32,730 --> 00:08:35,580
<i>At the edge of that shadow,</i> <i>I think...</i>

108
00:08:35,640 --> 00:08:37,680
<i>Me too.</i>

109
00:08:39,960 --> 00:08:41,910
<i>It's an indentation.</i>

110
00:08:41,980 --> 00:08:46,010
<i>Yes, about the size</i> <i>of a pencil point.</i>

111
00:08:46,080 --> 00:08:47,930
<i>Go to 40.</i>

112
00:08:56,320 --> 00:08:58,170
<i>Go to 60.</i>

113
00:09:04,030 --> 00:09:06,300
<i>Jeremy,</i> <i>do you think maybe...</i>

114
00:09:06,360 --> 00:09:09,080
<i>Maybe it's just</i> <i>a grain of sand.</i>

115
00:09:11,360 --> 00:09:13,210
<i>Go to 80.</i>

116
00:09:21,240 --> 00:09:23,130
<i>What about</i> <i>the bits of green?</i>

117
00:09:23,200 --> 00:09:25,020
<i>Paint.</i> <i>For God's sake!</i>

118
00:09:25,080 --> 00:09:27,510
<i>Pistachio ice cream!</i> <i>There's no basis to assume</i> <i>it's anything yet.</i>

119
00:09:27,580 --> 00:09:30,650
You're too good a scientist not to be thinking the same thing I am.

120
00:09:30,720 --> 00:09:35,540
<i>If this is really something new,</i> <i>some brand-new form of life...</i>

121
00:09:35,610 --> 00:09:37,980
The best hope of cracking it is to be grindingly thorough...

122
00:09:38,040 --> 00:09:41,010
with the help of computer number one.

123
00:09:41,080 --> 00:09:43,320
<i>Okay?</i> <i>Now let's get on with it.</i>

124
00:09:53,020 --> 00:09:55,510
<i>Hold it.</i>

125
00:09:57,050 --> 00:09:58,940
More pistachio?

126
00:10:00,220 --> 00:10:02,110
<i>I count four patches.</i>

127
00:10:02,170 --> 00:10:05,430
Keep going. I'll computerize the coordinates.

128
00:10:05,500 --> 00:10:07,890
Let's take a look at the rock at 100.

129
00:10:14,590 --> 00:10:17,170
<i>I doubt that's what knocked</i> <i>the capsule off trajectory.</i>

130
00:10:17,240 --> 00:10:19,480
Unless the rock was going at tremendous speed,

131
00:10:19,550 --> 00:10:21,270
or unless it's terribly heavy.

132
00:10:21,340 --> 00:10:23,350
For Pete's sake, Ruth, it can't be that heavy.

133
00:10:23,420 --> 00:10:25,310
Hall and I could lift the capsule.

134
00:10:25,370 --> 00:10:28,790
However, it's possible the rock is different in space; out there it might do anything.

135
00:10:28,860 --> 00:10:31,760
Maybe it has elastic properties we don't even know yet.

136
00:10:31,840 --> 00:10:34,840
Let's have a look at the green patches.

137
00:10:34,910 --> 00:10:38,010
They must've come off the rock,

138
00:10:38,080 --> 00:10:39,990
if it is rock.

139
00:10:42,910 --> 00:10:44,790
You know something?

140
00:10:44,860 --> 00:10:47,540
They do look like spatters of paint.

141
00:10:48,700 --> 00:10:51,120
Let's go back to the rock and see it at 440.

142
00:11:00,160 --> 00:11:02,910
<i>If that's a meteor,</i> <i>it's a damn peculiar one.</i>

143
00:11:04,410 --> 00:11:07,310
This left border over here,

144
00:11:08,800 --> 00:11:12,370
it's smooth, almost like an artificial surface.

145
00:11:12,440 --> 00:11:15,290
Painted, maybe. Luminous paint.

146
00:11:15,360 --> 00:11:18,620
If I keep watching it, I might think so.

147
00:11:18,680 --> 00:11:20,790
Wet paint sign and all.

148
00:11:24,160 --> 00:11:27,120
Jeremy? <i>What?</i>

149
00:11:29,600 --> 00:11:31,600
Nothing.

150
00:11:31,680 --> 00:11:33,750
You okay?

151
00:11:33,820 --> 00:11:37,050
It's just my eyes are tired. We've been at it five hours straight.

152
00:11:37,120 --> 00:11:38,970
We'll take a caffeine break in a minute.

153
00:11:39,040 --> 00:11:42,680
First I'd like to see one of the separate patches of green at 1,000.

154
00:11:54,840 --> 00:11:56,980
<i>Did you see that?</i> <i>I saw it.</i>

155
00:11:57,050 --> 00:11:59,670
You didn't change the lighting? <i>I didn't touch it.</i>

156
00:12:02,590 --> 00:12:04,950
<i>Looks alive.</i> <i>Yes.</i>

157
00:12:05,020 --> 00:12:06,840
<i>It's bigger</i> <i>than two microns.</i>

158
00:12:06,910 --> 00:12:10,900
Which means the infection is spread by a mere fraction of the green.

159
00:12:10,970 --> 00:12:12,690
I'm bringing down cameras.

160
00:12:12,760 --> 00:12:14,620
Let's have the other microscanner.

161
00:12:20,060 --> 00:12:23,600
Stone to Level Control. I need a Mic-T. <i>Roger. Will send.</i>

162
00:12:25,660 --> 00:12:28,210
<i>Jump it up to 1500.</i>

163
00:12:28,280 --> 00:12:30,390
Microscan doesn't go any higher.

164
00:12:30,460 --> 00:12:33,360
We can get 1500 light magnification in microchemistry.

165
00:12:33,440 --> 00:12:35,380
I'll send the rock through.

166
00:12:37,630 --> 00:12:40,480
<i>Attention C.L.T.s</i> <i>on levels 4 and 5.</i>

167
00:12:40,540 --> 00:12:44,790
<i>Main computer shows capacity</i> <i>versus access time...</i>

168
00:12:44,860 --> 00:12:47,230
<i>at ten to the twelfth bits.</i>

169
00:12:47,290 --> 00:12:49,750
<i>For any change</i> <i>in memory configuration,</i>

170
00:12:49,820 --> 00:12:53,230
<i>C.L.T.s must check</i> <i>their unicom op.</i>

171
00:13:39,740 --> 00:13:41,590
<i>Beautiful, sir.</i>

172
00:13:41,660 --> 00:13:43,670
I'm the Mic-T. You're real sharp on the hands.

173
00:13:43,740 --> 00:13:46,260
Thanks. Nice to know one hasn't lost one's touch.

174
00:13:46,330 --> 00:13:48,190
The next step is to find out what makes it grow.

175
00:13:48,250 --> 00:13:51,320
We'll need samples from the scoop to send through maxcult for culture and isolation.

176
00:13:51,390 --> 00:13:53,490
Roger, sir. In work.

177
00:13:57,020 --> 00:13:59,470
<i>Good God!</i>

178
00:14:17,180 --> 00:14:19,550
It's growing.

179
00:14:34,840 --> 00:14:36,700
<i>Not so good.</i>

180
00:14:36,760 --> 00:14:40,410
<i>Naturally he has acidosis.</i> <i>His blood pH was</i> <i>nine points off normal.</i>

181
00:14:40,480 --> 00:14:44,500
But why? Stupid machine! What makes his blood too acid?

182
00:14:44,570 --> 00:14:46,740
Ask the patient.

183
00:15:01,500 --> 00:15:05,010
<i>Bio-safety to S.L.,</i> <i>sectors 3 and 6.</i>

184
00:15:05,080 --> 00:15:07,350
<i>Give us a code 3</i> <i>when you get it.</i>

185
00:15:13,820 --> 00:15:15,670
Mr. Jackson?

186
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:23,260
Now, don't be scared. I'm a doctor.

187
00:15:25,790 --> 00:15:27,640
Bull.

188
00:15:29,370 --> 00:15:31,030
Where am I?

189
00:15:31,100 --> 00:15:33,820
A special laboratory in Nevada.

190
00:15:33,880 --> 00:15:36,980
We brought you here from Piedmont. You're sick.

191
00:15:38,750 --> 00:15:41,270
It's this damn stomach of mine.

192
00:15:41,340 --> 00:15:44,500
Bleeding? Hell, yes, bleeding!

193
00:15:44,570 --> 00:15:46,910
Bleeding in your stomach? You have an ulcer?

194
00:15:46,970 --> 00:15:50,580
Damn tootin'. Two years.

195
00:15:50,650 --> 00:15:53,140
But you must have pain. What do you do for it?

196
00:15:55,480 --> 00:15:58,200
Aspirin...

197
00:15:58,270 --> 00:16:00,180
and squeeze.

198
00:16:00,250 --> 00:16:04,380
Squeeze? What's that? Ain't gonna tell ya.

199
00:16:19,580 --> 00:16:23,130
So you're a Sterno drinker, huh?

200
00:16:23,200 --> 00:16:25,050
Works good.

201
00:16:30,490 --> 00:16:33,040
Give him squeeze.

202
00:16:40,960 --> 00:16:43,260
What's the baby's name, Mr. Jackson?

203
00:16:44,120 --> 00:16:47,510
- You the nurse? - Uh-huh.

204
00:16:49,280 --> 00:16:51,480
Shoot!

205
00:16:51,550 --> 00:16:53,400
Can't see your legs.

206
00:16:57,340 --> 00:16:59,440
Do you know the baby's name?

207
00:17:00,860 --> 00:17:02,750
Give us a butt first.

208
00:17:02,810 --> 00:17:04,720
Smoking isn't allowed here.

209
00:17:06,270 --> 00:17:08,340
Then go fish.

210
00:17:14,270 --> 00:17:16,240
Yeah. When you're finished,

211
00:17:16,320 --> 00:17:19,350
we'll transfuse Jackson and start ice water lavage.

212
00:17:19,420 --> 00:17:21,910
He has a two-year history of bleeding ulcers.

213
00:17:21,980 --> 00:17:25,240
You seem delighted. It may be the reason he survived.

214
00:17:26,720 --> 00:17:29,500
If only our young gourmet weren't so normal.

215
00:17:29,560 --> 00:17:32,250
Well, let's hope nothing changes that.

216
00:17:32,320 --> 00:17:34,420
We might have to before this is over.

217
00:18:09,340 --> 00:18:11,670
They should've dropped the bomb.

218
00:18:11,740 --> 00:18:14,970
They should've dropped it two days ago, General.

219
00:18:15,040 --> 00:18:18,040
This Phantom crashed a good 60 miles beyond the cordoned area.

220
00:18:18,110 --> 00:18:20,280
Men on the ground can't cordon off airspace, sir.

221
00:18:20,350 --> 00:18:22,420
I just don't understand why the Wildfire Team...

222
00:18:22,490 --> 00:18:25,520
hasn't beefed about the delay in 7-12.

223
00:18:25,600 --> 00:18:27,600
It's been almost 24 hours, and not a word from them.

224
00:18:27,680 --> 00:18:31,120
I don't think Piedmont had anything to do with this crash, Manchek.

225
00:18:31,200 --> 00:18:33,560
It was a fluke.

226
00:18:33,630 --> 00:18:38,170
That plane was only over the W.F. area for two minutes at 23,000 feet.

227
00:18:38,240 --> 00:18:40,570
It's a routine training mission accident, I bet you.

228
00:18:40,640 --> 00:18:42,420
Pilot error. Let's go.

229
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:50,070
Check with Wildfire Message Center, Delta Five.

230
00:18:50,140 --> 00:18:51,990
Make sure everything there is nominal.

231
00:18:52,060 --> 00:18:55,470
Send me word on scrambler at Big Head crash base. Okay.

232
00:19:01,760 --> 00:19:05,370
Checklim program completed. All circuit banks nominal.

233
00:19:14,590 --> 00:19:16,790
Same thing on the M.C.N. console, Captain.

234
00:19:18,720 --> 00:19:20,570
<i>Just a minute, Dr. Robertson.</i>

235
00:19:20,640 --> 00:19:23,860
<i>You're saying Stone's</i> <i>$90 million facility,</i> <i>which you recommended,</i>

236
00:19:23,930 --> 00:19:26,420
<i>was knocked out</i> <i>by a sliver of paper?</i>

237
00:19:26,490 --> 00:19:29,140
<i>You tell that</i> <i>to the taxpayers!</i>

238
00:19:29,210 --> 00:19:32,110
<i>These were highly-trained</i> <i>electronics men, Senator,</i>

239
00:19:32,190 --> 00:19:34,190
<i>looking for</i> <i>an electronic fault.</i>

240
00:19:34,270 --> 00:19:37,460
<i>The trouble was</i> <i>purely mechanical</i> <i>of the simplest kind.</i>

241
00:19:37,530 --> 00:19:41,180
<i>But for them, it was like</i> <i>trying to see an elephant</i> <i>through a microscope.</i>

242
00:19:41,240 --> 00:19:43,130
<i>The sliver had peeled</i> <i>from the roll...</i>

243
00:19:43,200 --> 00:19:46,130
<i>and wedged between the bell</i> <i>and striker, preventing the bell</i> <i>from ringing.</i>

244
00:19:53,500 --> 00:19:57,010
I'm convinced we're being held incommunicado.

245
00:19:57,080 --> 00:20:00,980
Very flattering. We don't know much more than when we got here.

246
00:20:01,050 --> 00:20:02,910
We know about Scoop now.

247
00:20:02,970 --> 00:20:06,200
It's possible what Scoop found was no accident.

248
00:20:06,270 --> 00:20:09,300
I suspect they were looking for the ultimate biological weapon.

249
00:20:09,370 --> 00:20:13,840
Sounds like you're getting a little paranoid in this fun house.

250
00:20:13,920 --> 00:20:18,140
What does Stone think... about the ultimate weapon, I mean?

251
00:20:18,200 --> 00:20:20,850
We've isolated the organism.

252
00:20:20,920 --> 00:20:23,090
It's in microchemistry.

253
00:20:23,160 --> 00:20:26,580
We'll show you. <i>Watchdog to electrical support...</i>

254
00:21:31,160 --> 00:21:32,890
All right, Lieutenant.

255
00:21:32,960 --> 00:21:36,530
Albuquerque Center, this is Air Force 561.

256
00:21:36,600 --> 00:21:39,190
Go ahead 561. My air hose is coming apart...

257
00:21:39,260 --> 00:21:41,110
like it's dissolving!

258
00:21:41,180 --> 00:21:43,760
Everything made of rubber is coming apart!

259
00:21:43,830 --> 00:21:46,580
I feel funny.

260
00:21:50,300 --> 00:21:53,780
It's a fluke, a vibration effect maybe.

261
00:21:53,850 --> 00:21:56,090
Let's get up there.

262
00:21:56,160 --> 00:21:58,390
Has Wildfire been informed? You mean the germ people?

263
00:21:58,460 --> 00:22:02,100
It went out to them on the scrambler an hour ago. This they can't ignore.

264
00:22:25,400 --> 00:22:29,400
<i>I.B. control</i> <i>to cafeteria level 3.</i>

265
00:22:29,470 --> 00:22:31,470
<i>Number 4 Charlie hatch</i> <i>shows condition blue.</i>

266
00:22:31,550 --> 00:22:35,890
<i>Alter responsivity characteristics</i> <i>until you get condition green.</i>

267
00:22:42,880 --> 00:22:44,730
Ready.

268
00:22:52,600 --> 00:22:55,900
<i>Nothing so unusual</i> <i>about our rock after all.</i>

269
